<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Vowel-Heavy Rack Solutions</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6">What to do when your rack looks like a Hawaiian dictionary</p>

<p class="text-lg text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-8">You draw your tiles and see A-A-E-I-O-U-T. Six vowels and one lonely consonant. This happens more often than you'd think — the Scrabble bag contains 42 vowels out of 98 tiles (43%). The key isn't panic; it's having a rehearsed strategy for efficiently dumping vowels while maintaining scoring position.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">What Constitutes Vowel-Heavy</h2>

<p>The ideal rack balance is 3 vowels and 4 consonants (or 4/3 in some situations). Here's how to categorise your rack imbalance:</p>

<div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
<table class="min-w-full text-sm">
<thead><tr class="border-b border-gray-700"><th class="text-left py-2 text-amber-400">Vowel Count</th><th class="text-left py-2 text-amber-400">Severity</th><th class="text-left py-2 text-amber-400">Action</th></tr></thead>
<tbody class="text-gray-300">
<tr class="border-b border-gray-800"><td class="py-2">3 vowels</td><td class="text-green-400">Ideal</td><td>Play normally</td></tr>
<tr class="border-b border-gray-800"><td class="py-2">4 vowels</td><td class="text-yellow-400">Slightly heavy</td><td>Prefer plays that shed 1-2 vowels</td></tr>
<tr class="border-b border-gray-800"><td class="py-2">5 vowels</td><td class="text-orange-400">Heavy</td><td>Use vowel-dump words or exchange 3-4 vowels</td></tr>
<tr class="border-b border-gray-800"><td class="py-2">6 vowels</td><td class="text-red-400">Severe</td><td>Exchange or play multi-vowel word immediately</td></tr>
<tr class="border-b border-gray-800"><td class="py-2">7 vowels</td><td class="text-red-500">Critical</td><td>Exchange 5-6 tiles, keep only useful vowels</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Best Vowel-Dump Words</h2>

<p>These words contain multiple vowels and can rescue a flooded rack. Memorise them by vowel count:</p>

<div class="border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
  <p class="text-blue-300 font-semibold mb-2">4-Vowel Words (Shed 4 vowels in one play)</p>
  <ul class="text-gray-300 space-y-1 mt-2">
    <li><strong>ADIEU</strong> — (6 pts) A farewell. Uses A, I, E, U.</li>
    <li><strong>AUDIO</strong> — (6 pts) Sound reproduction. Uses A, U, I, O.</li>
    <li><strong>OURIE</strong> — (5 pts) Chilly (Scottish). Uses O, U, I, E.</li>
    <li><strong>URAEI</strong> — (5 pts) Plural of uraeus. Uses U, A, E, I.</li>
    <li><strong>LOOIE</strong> — (5 pts) Lieutenant (slang). Uses O, O, I, E.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
  <p class="text-purple-300 font-semibold mb-2">3-Vowel Words (Common and reliable)</p>
  <ul class="text-gray-300 space-y-1 mt-2">
    <li><strong>AIOLI</strong> — (5 pts) Garlic mayonnaise. Three vowels out of 5 letters.</li>
    <li><strong>OORIE</strong> — (5 pts) Cold, chilly. Three vowels.</li>
    <li><strong>OUIJA</strong> — (12 pts) Spirit board. High-scoring dump with J.</li>
    <li><strong>NAEVI</strong> — (8 pts) Plural of naevus (birthmarks). Uses A, E, I.</li>
    <li><strong>AREAE</strong> — (5 pts) Plural of area. Dumps A, E, A, E.</li>
    <li><strong>AQUAE</strong> — (14 pts) Plural of aqua. Uses Q without U-after pattern.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Exchange vs Play Through — The Decision Framework</h2>

<p>The eternal question: should you exchange tiles or play a low-scoring word to shed vowels? Here's a structured decision tree:</p>

<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-gray-300 my-6">
  <li><strong>Can you score 20+ while shedding 2+ vowels?</strong> → Always play. Any 20-point vowel-dump word is a great result.</li>
  <li><strong>Can you score 15-19 while shedding 2+ vowels?</strong> → Play in most situations. Only exchange if you're behind by 50+ and need a bingo.</li>
  <li><strong>Can you score 10-14 while shedding 2+ vowels?</strong> → Close call. Play if the board is tight or you're ahead. Exchange if you need a momentum shift.</li>
  <li><strong>Can you only score under 10?</strong> → Exchange 4-5 vowels. The lost turn is offset by much better rack quality next turn.</li>
  <li><strong>5+ vowels with no vowel-dump word available?</strong> → Exchange immediately. Keeping 5+ vowels hoping to draw consonants is statistically poor.</li>
</ol>

<div class="border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
  <p class="text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-2">Exchange Statistics</p>
  <ul class="text-gray-300 space-y-1 mt-2">
    <li>• Average points lost by exchanging: 22 (opponent's turn score)</li>
    <li>• Average points gained next turn with balanced rack: 32</li>
    <li>• Net benefit of exchanging vs playing a 6-point vowel dump: +4 points over 2 turns</li>
    <li>• Probability of drawing 2+ consonants when exchanging 4 tiles: 78%</li>
  </ul>
</div>

