<div class="border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
  <p class="text-purple-300 font-semibold mb-2">Pro Tip</p>
  <p class="text-gray-300">Playing AA on a Double Word Score gives you 4 points while dumping 2 vowels. It's not glamorous, but it's almost always better than exchanging when you only have 4 vowels. Save your exchange for truly hopeless racks (5+ vowels, no playable dump).</p>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Preventing Vowel-Heavy Racks Through Leave Management</h2>

<p>The best strategy is prevention. Smart leave management after every play keeps your rack balanced:</p>

<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 my-4">
  <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-indigo-900/40 border border-indigo-500/30 rounded-full text-xs text-indigo-300">Keep 2-3 vowels</span>
  <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-indigo-900/40 border border-indigo-500/30 rounded-full text-xs text-indigo-300">Shed duplicate vowels</span>
  <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-indigo-900/40 border border-indigo-500/30 rounded-full text-xs text-indigo-300">Avoid vowel-only leaves</span>
  <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-indigo-900/40 border border-indigo-500/30 rounded-full text-xs text-indigo-300">Track remaining tiles</span>
</div>

<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-gray-300 my-6">
  <li><strong>Never leave 3+ vowels behind</strong> — If your best play uses only consonants and leaves you with A-E-I-O, find a slightly lower-scoring play that sheds at least one vowel</li>
  <li><strong>Prioritise shedding duplicates</strong> — Two As on your rack are much worse than one A and one E. Plays that remove duplicate vowels are worth 3-5 points of sacrifice</li>
  <li><strong>Track bag composition</strong> — Late in the game, if 8+ vowels remain in the bag and you currently hold 3, consider shedding one preemptively</li>
  <li><strong>Use blank tiles for consonants</strong> — If you have a blank and a vowel-heavy rack, use the blank as a consonant (S, T, R, N) rather than wasting it as a vowel</li>
  <li><strong>Value E over other vowels</strong> — E combines with more consonants for bingos. When choosing which vowel to keep, E wins almost always</li>
</ol>

